english:
  title: A Palindromic Poem Presented to the Prime Minister
  author: Lee In-ro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In youth I pursued learning to seek office,
    Yet poems alone came forth, and suffering endless.
    My aging heart stirs like spring's tangled willow down,
    My graying temples wear the frost of dawn anew.

    The rice jar tips—the morning meal runs dry,
    Hungry belly cries out through the night.
    My heart yearns earnestly to repay kindness,
    But who will save this withered fish?

    Who will rescue this desiccated fish?
    Earnest still, the thought of repaying grace—
    The belly groans and rumbles through the night,
    No morning gruel as the jar lies overturned.
    Fresh frost has whitened my cheeks at dawn,
    Tangled willows cloud my aging spring thoughts,
    My poems achieved, all labor wrought in vain—
    I sought office through early study's toil.
  footnotes:
    - This is a huimun (回文) or palindromic poem, a Korean poetic form where the second half mirrors and reverses the first half. The work demonstrates the virtuosity characteristic of Goryeo literary culture.
    - The 'withered fish' (枯鱗) is a metaphor for the poet's own impoverished condition and his hope for patronage and aid.
    - The poem laments the gap between scholarly ambition and material hardship, expressing both gratitude for past support and anxiety about survival.
